# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mlflow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mlflow/experiment] An **experiment** is a procedure carried out to support or refute a hypothesis, or determine the efficacy or likelihood of something previously untried.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments provide insight into cause-and-effect by demonstrating what outcome occurs when a particular factor is manipulated.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments vary greatly in goal and scale but always rely on repeatable procedure and logical analysis of the results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] There also exist natural experimental studies.
[src:mlflow/experiment] A child may carry out basic experiments to understand how things fall to the ground, while teams of scientists may take years of systematic investigation to advance their understanding of a phenomenon.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments and other types of hands-on activities are very important to student learning in the science classroom.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments can raise test scores and help a student become more engaged and interested in the material they are learning, especially when used over time.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments can vary from personal and informal natural comparisons (e.g. tasting a range of chocolates to find a favorite), to highly controlled (e.g. tests requiring complex apparatus overseen by many scientists that hope to discover information about subatomic particles).
[src:mlflow/experiment] Uses of experiments vary considerably between the natural and human sciences.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments typically include controls, which are designed to minimize the effects of variables other than the single independent variable.
[src:mlflow/experiment] This increases the reliability of the results, often through a comparison between control measurements and the other measurements.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Scientific controls are a part of the scientific method.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Ideally, all variables in an experiment are controlled (accounted for by the control measurements) and none are uncontrolled.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In such an experiment, if all controls work as expected, it is possible to conclude that the experiment works as intended, and that results are due to the effect of the tested variables.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the scientific method, an experiment is an empirical procedure that arbitrates competing models or hypotheses.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Researchers also use experimentation to test existing theories or new hypotheses to support or disprove them.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An experiment usually tests a hypothesis, which is an expectation about how a particular process or phenomenon works.
[src:mlflow/experiment] However, an experiment may also aim to answer a "what-if" question, without a specific expectation about what the experiment reveals, or to confirm prior results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] If an experiment is carefully conducted, the results usually either support or disprove the hypothesis.
[src:mlflow/experiment] According to some philosophies of science, an experiment can never "prove" a hypothesis, it can only add support.
[src:mlflow/experiment] On the other hand, an experiment that provides a counterexample can disprove a theory or hypothesis, but a theory can always be salvaged by appropriate ad hoc modifications at the expense of simplicity.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An experiment must also control the possible confounding factors—any factors that would mar the accuracy or repeatability of the experiment or the ability to interpret the results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Confounding is commonly eliminated through scientific controls and/or, in randomized experiments, through random assignment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In engineering and the physical sciences, experiments are a primary component of the scientific method.
[src:mlflow/experiment] They are used to test theories and hypotheses about how physical processes work under particular conditions (e.g., whether a particular engineering process can produce a desired chemical compound).
[src:mlflow/experiment] Typically, experiments in these fields focus on replication of identical procedures in hopes of producing identical results in each replication.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In medicine and the social sciences, the prevalence of experimental research varies widely across disciplines.
[src:mlflow/experiment] When used, however, experiments typically follow the form of the clinical trial, where experimental units (usually individual human beings) are randomly assigned to a treatment or control condition where one or more outcomes are assessed.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In contrast to norms in the physical sciences, the focus is typically on the average treatment effect (the difference in outcomes between the treatment and control groups) or another test statistic produced by the experiment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] A single study typically does not involve replications of the experiment, but separate studies may be aggregated through systematic review and meta-analysis.
[src:mlflow/experiment] There are various differences in experimental practice in each of the branches of science.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Several scholars have noted that the account in *Daniel* 1:12–16 contains one of the earliest descriptions of a controlled comparative test in ancient literature.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the narrative, Daniel and his companions request a ten-day trial in which they consume only vegetables and water, while other youths continue on the king’s diet.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The results of the two regimens are compared, and the steward is instructed to act based on the observable outcome.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Historians of science have occasionally referenced this passage as an early literary example of empirical reasoning.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Lindberg notes that the Hebrew Bible contains "procedures that resemble empirical testing," and includes Daniel 1 among examples where a trial is deliberately arranged to evaluate competing conditions.
[src:mlflow/experiment] VanderKam likewise describes the episode as presenting "a rudimentary experimental design" contrasting two diets under controlled circumstances.
[src:mlflow/experiment] While this view is not universal, some commentators have referred to the episode as one of the earliest recorded experimental tests.
[src:mlflow/experiment] One of the first methodical approaches to experiments in the modern sense is visible in the works of the Arab mathematician and scholar Ibn al-Haytham.
[src:mlflow/experiment] He conducted his experiments in the field of optics—going back to optical and mathematical problems in the works of Ptolemy—by controlling his experiments due to factors such as self-criticality, reliance on visible results of the experiments as well as a criticality in terms of earlier results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] He was one of the first scholars to use an inductive-experimental method for achieving results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] According to his explanation, a strictly controlled test execution with a sensibility for the subjectivity and susceptibility of outcomes due to the nature of man is necessary.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Thus, a comparison of earlier results with the experimental results is necessary for an objective experiment—the visible results being more important.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the end, this may mean that an experimental researcher must find enough courage to discard traditional opinions or results, especially if these results are not experimental but results from a logical/ mental derivation.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In this process of critical consideration, the man himself should not forget that he tends to subjective opinions—through "prejudices" and "leniency"—and thus has to be critical about his own way of building hypotheses.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Francis Bacon (1561–1626), an English philosopher and scientist active in the 17th century, became an influential supporter of experimental science in the English renaissance.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Notably, he first ordered the scientific method as we understand it today.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the centuries that followed, people who applied the scientific method in different areas made important advances and discoveries.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, Galileo Galilei (1564–1642) accurately measured time and experimented to make accurate measurements and conclusions about the speed of a falling body.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Antoine Lavoisier (1743–1794), a French chemist, used experiment to describe new areas, such as combustion and biochemistry and to develop the theory of conservation of mass (matter).
[src:mlflow/experiment] Louis Pasteur (1822–1895) used the scientific method to disprove the prevailing theory of spontaneous generation and to develop the germ theory of disease.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Because of the importance of controlling potentially confounding variables, the use of well-designed laboratory experiments is preferred when possible.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments might be categorized according to a number of dimensions, depending upon professional norms and standards in different fields of study.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In some disciplines (e.g., psychology or political science), a 'true experiment' is a method of social research in which there are two kinds of variables.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The independent variable is manipulated by the experimenter, and the dependent variable is measured.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The signifying characteristic of a true experiment is that it randomly allocates the subjects to neutralize experimenter bias, and ensures, over a large number of iterations of the experiment, that it controls for all confounding factors.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Depending on the discipline, experiments can be conducted to accomplish different but not mutually exclusive goals: test theories, search for and document phenomena, develop theories, or advise policymakers.
[src:mlflow/experiment] These goals also relate differently to validity concerns.
[src:mlflow/experiment] A controlled experiment often compares the results obtained from experimental samples against *control* samples, which are practically identical to the experimental sample except for the one aspect whose effect is being tested (the independent variable).
[src:mlflow/experiment] The sample or group receiving the drug would be the experimental group (treatment group); and the one receiving the placebo or regular treatment would be the control one.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In many laboratory experiments it is good practice to have several replicate samples for the test being performed and have both a positive control and a negative control.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Most often, tests are done in duplicate or triplicate.
[src:mlflow/experiment] A positive control is a procedure similar to the actual experimental test but is known from previous experience to give a positive result.
[src:mlflow/experiment] A negative control is known to give a negative result.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The positive control confirms that the basic conditions of the experiment were able to produce a positive result, even if none of the actual experimental samples produce a positive result.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The negative control demonstrates the base-line result obtained when a test does not produce a measurable positive result.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Most often the value of the negative control is treated as a "background" value to subtract from the test sample results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Sometimes the positive control takes the quadrant of a standard curve.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An example that is often used in teaching laboratories is a controlled protein assay.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Students might be given a fluid sample containing an unknown (to the student) amount of protein.
[src:mlflow/experiment] It is their job to correctly perform a controlled experiment in which they determine the concentration of protein in the fluid sample (usually called the "unknown sample").
[src:mlflow/experiment] The teaching lab would be equipped with a protein standard solution with a known protein concentration.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Students could make several positive control samples containing various dilutions of the protein standard.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Negative control samples would contain all of the reagents for the protein assay but no protein.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In this example, all samples are performed in duplicate.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The assay is a colorimetric assay in which a spectrophotometer can measure the amount of protein in samples by detecting a colored complex formed by the interaction of protein molecules and molecules of an added dye.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the illustration, the results for the diluted test samples can be compared to the results of the standard curve (the blue line in the illustration) to estimate the amount of protein in the unknown sample.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Controlled experiments can be performed when it is difficult to exactly control all the conditions in an experiment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In this case, the experiment begins by creating two or more sample groups that are probabilistically equivalent, which means that measurements of traits should be similar among the groups and that the groups should respond in the same manner if given the same treatment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] This equivalency is determined by statistical methods that take into account the amount of variation between individuals and the number of individuals in each group.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In fields such as microbiology and chemistry, where there is very little variation between individuals and the group size is easily in the millions, these statistical methods are often bypassed and simply splitting a solution into equal parts is assumed to produce identical sample groups.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Once equivalent groups have been formed, the experimenter tries to treat them identically except for the one *variable* that he or she wishes to isolate.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Human experimentation requires special safeguards against outside variables such as the *placebo effect*.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Such experiments are generally *double blind*, meaning that neither the volunteer nor the researcher knows which individuals are in the control group or the experimental group until after all of the data have been collected.
[src:mlflow/experiment] This ensures that any effects on the volunteer are due to the treatment itself and are not a response to the knowledge that he is being treated.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In human experiments, researchers may give a subject (person) a stimulus that the subject responds to.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The goal of the experiment is to measure the response to the stimulus by a test method.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In the design of experiments, two or more "treatments" are applied to estimate the difference between the mean responses for the treatments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, an experiment on baking bread could estimate the difference in the responses associated with quantitative variables, such as the ratio of water to flour, and with qualitative variables, such as strains of yeast.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experimentation is the step in the scientific method that helps people decide between two or more competing explanations—or hypotheses.
[src:mlflow/experiment] These hypotheses suggest reasons to explain a phenomenon or predict the results of an action.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An example might be the hypothesis that "if I release this ball, it will fall to the floor": this suggestion can then be tested by carrying out the experiment of letting go of the ball, and observing the results.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Formally, a hypothesis is compared against its opposite or null hypothesis ("if I release this ball, it will not fall to the floor").
[src:mlflow/experiment] The null hypothesis is that there is no explanation or predictive power of the phenomenon through the reasoning that is being investigated.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Once hypotheses are defined, an experiment can be carried out and the results analysed to confirm, refute, or define the accuracy of the hypotheses.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Experiments can be also designed to estimate spillover effects onto nearby untreated units.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The term "experiment" usually implies a controlled experiment, but sometimes controlled experiments are prohibitively difficult, impossible, unethical or illegal.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In this case researchers resort to natural experiments or quasi-experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Natural experiments rely solely on observations of the variables of the system under study, rather than manipulation of just one or a few variables as occurs in controlled experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] To the degree possible, they attempt to collect data for the system in such a way that contribution from all variables can be determined, and where the effects of variation in certain variables remain approximately constant so that the effects of other variables can be discerned.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The degree to which this is possible depends on the observed correlation between explanatory variables in the observed data.
[src:mlflow/experiment] When these variables are *not* well correlated, natural experiments can approach the power of controlled experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Usually, however, there is some correlation between these variables, which reduces the reliability of natural experiments relative to what could be concluded if a controlled experiment were performed.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Also, because natural experiments usually take place in uncontrolled environments, variables from undetected sources are neither measured nor held constant, and these may produce illusory correlations in variables under study.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Much research in several science disciplines, including economics, human geography, archaeology, sociology, cultural anthropology, geology, paleontology, ecology, meteorology, and astronomy, relies on quasi-experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, in astronomy it is clearly impossible, when testing the hypothesis "Stars are collapsed clouds of hydrogen", to start out with a giant cloud of hydrogen, and then perform the experiment of waiting a few billion years for it to form a star.
[src:mlflow/experiment] However, by observing various clouds of hydrogen in various states of collapse, and other implications of the hypothesis (for example, the presence of various spectral emissions from the light of stars), we can collect data we require to support the hypothesis.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An early example of this type of experiment was the first verification in the 17th century that light does not travel from place to place instantaneously, but instead has a measurable speed.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Field experiments are so named to distinguish them from laboratory experiments, which enforce scientific control by testing a hypothesis in the artificial and highly controlled setting of a laboratory.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Often used in the social sciences, and especially in economic analyses of education and health interventions, field experiments have the advantage that outcomes are observed in a natural setting rather than in a contrived laboratory environment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For this reason, field experiments are sometimes seen as having higher external validity than laboratory experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] However, like natural experiments, field experiments suffer from the possibility of contamination: experimental conditions can be controlled with more precision and certainty in the lab.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Yet some phenomena (e.g., voter turnout in an election) cannot be easily studied in a laboratory.
[src:mlflow/experiment] An observational study is used when it is impractical, unethical, cost-prohibitive (or otherwise inefficient) to fit a physical or social system into a laboratory setting, to completely control confounding factors, or to apply random assignment.
[src:mlflow/experiment] It can also be used when confounding factors are either limited or known well enough to analyze the data in light of them (though this may be rare when social phenomena are under examination).
[src:mlflow/experiment] For an observational science to be valid, the experimenter must know and account for confounding factors.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In these situations, observational studies have value because they often suggest hypotheses that can be tested with randomized experiments or by collecting fresh data.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Fundamentally, however, observational studies are not experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] By definition, observational studies lack the manipulation required for Baconian experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In addition, observational studies (e.g., in biological or social systems) often involve variables that are difficult to quantify or control.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Observational studies are limited because they lack the statistical properties of randomized experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In a randomized experiment, the method of randomization specified in the experimental protocol guides the statistical analysis, which is usually specified also by the experimental protocol.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Without a statistical model that reflects an objective randomization, the statistical analysis relies on a subjective model.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Inferences from subjective models are unreliable in theory and practice.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In fact, there are several cases where carefully conducted observational studies consistently give wrong results, that is, where the results of the observational studies are inconsistent and also differ from the results of experiments.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, epidemiological studies of colon cancer consistently show beneficial correlations with broccoli consumption, while experiments find no benefit.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In contrast, randomization implies that for each covariate, the mean for each group is expected to be the same.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For any randomized trial, some variation from the mean is expected, of course, but the randomization ensures that the experimental groups have mean values that are close, due to the central limit theorem and Markov's inequality.
[src:mlflow/experiment] With inadequate randomization or low sample size, the systematic variation in covariates between the treatment groups (or exposure groups) makes it difficult to separate the effect of the treatment (exposure) from the effects of the other covariates, most of which have not been measured.
[src:mlflow/experiment] The mathematical models used to analyze such data must consider each differing covariate (if measured), and results are not meaningful if a covariate is neither randomized nor included in the model.
[src:mlflow/experiment] To avoid conditions that render an experiment far less useful, physicians conducting medical trials—say for U.S.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Food and Drug Administration approval—quantify and randomize the covariates that can be identified.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Researchers attempt to reduce the biases of observational studies with matching methods such as propensity score matching, which require large populations of subjects and extensive information on covariates.
[src:mlflow/experiment] However, propensity score matching is no longer recommended as a technique because it can increase, rather than decrease, bias.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Outcomes are also quantified when possible (bone density, the amount of some cell or substance in the blood, physical strength or endurance, etc.) and not based on a subject's or a professional observer's opinion.
[src:mlflow/experiment] In this way, the design of an observational study can render the results more objective and therefore, more convincing.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, in psychology or health care, it is unethical to provide a substandard treatment to patients.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Therefore, ethical review boards are supposed to stop clinical trials and other experiments unless a new treatment is believed to offer benefits as good as current best practice.
[src:mlflow/experiment] It is also generally unethical (and often illegal) to conduct randomized experiments on the effects of substandard or harmful treatments, such as the effects of ingesting arsenic on human health.
[src:mlflow/experiment] To understand the effects of such exposures, scientists sometimes use observational studies to understand the effects of those factors.
[src:mlflow/experiment] Even when experimental research does not directly involve human subjects, it may still present ethical concerns.
[src:mlflow/experiment] For example, the nuclear bomb experiments conducted by the Manhattan Project implied the use of nuclear reactions to harm human beings even though the experiments did not directly involve any human subjects.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In machine learning, **hyperparameter optimization** or tuning is the problem of choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A hyperparameter is a parameter whose value is used to control the learning process, which must be configured before the process starts.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperparameter optimization determines the set of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on a given data set.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] The objective function takes a set of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Cross-validation is often used to estimate this generalization performance, and therefore choose the set of values for hyperparameters that maximize it.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] The traditional method for hyperparameter optimization has been *grid search*, or a *parameter sweep*, which is simply an exhaustive searching through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space of a learning algorithm.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A grid search algorithm must be guided by some performance metric, typically measured by cross-validation on the training set or evaluation on a hold-out validation set.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Since the parameter space of a machine learner may include real-valued or unbounded value spaces for certain parameters, manually set bounds and discretization may be necessary before applying grid search.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] For example, a typical soft-margin SVM classifier equipped with an RBF kernel has at least two hyperparameters that need to be tuned for good performance on unseen data: a regularization constant *C* and a kernel hyperparameter γ.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search then trains an SVM with each pair (*C*, γ) in the Cartesian product of these two sets and evaluates their performance on a held-out validation set (or by internal cross-validation on the training set, in which case multiple SVMs are trained per pair).
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Finally, the grid search algorithm outputs the settings that achieved the highest score in the validation procedure.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search suffers from the curse of dimensionality, but is often embarrassingly parallel because the hyperparameter settings it evaluates are typically independent of each other.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search replaces the exhaustive enumeration of all combinations by selecting them randomly.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be simply applied to the discrete setting described above, but also generalizes to continuous and mixed spaces.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A benefit over grid search is that random search can explore many more values than grid search could for continuous hyperparameters.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] It can outperform Grid search, especially when only a small number of hyperparameters affects the final performance of the machine learning algorithm.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In this case, the optimization problem is said to have a low intrinsic dimensionality.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search is also embarrassingly parallel, and additionally allows the inclusion of prior knowledge by specifying the distribution from which to sample.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Despite its simplicity, random search remains one of the important base-lines against which to compare the performance of new hyperparameter optimization methods.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Bayesian optimization is a global optimization method for noisy black-box functions.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Applied to hyperparameter optimization, Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic model of the function mapping from hyperparameter values to the objective evaluated on a validation set.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] By iteratively evaluating a promising hyperparameter configuration based on the current model, and then updating it, Bayesian optimization aims to gather observations revealing as much information as possible about this function and, in particular, the location of the optimum.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] It tries to balance exploration (hyperparameters for which the outcome is most uncertain) and exploitation (hyperparameters expected close to the optimum).
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In practice, Bayesian optimization has been shown to obtain better results in fewer evaluations compared to grid search and random search, due to the ability to reason about the quality of experiments before they are run.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] For specific learning algorithms, it is possible to compute the gradient with respect to hyperparameters and then optimize the hyperparameters using gradient descent.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] The first usage of these techniques was focused on neural networks.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Since then, these methods have been extended to other models such as support vector machines or logistic regression.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A different approach in order to obtain a gradient with respect to hyperparameters consists in differentiating the steps of an iterative optimization algorithm using automatic differentiation.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A more recent work along this direction uses the implicit function theorem to calculate hypergradients and proposes a stable approximation of the inverse Hessian.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] The method scales to millions of hyperparameters and requires constant memory.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In a different approach, a hypernetwork is trained to approximate the best response function.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] One of the advantages of this method is that it can handle discrete hyperparameters as well.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Self-tuning networks offer a memory efficient version of this approach by choosing a compact representation for the hypernetwork.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Apart from hypernetwork approaches, gradient-based methods can be used to optimize discrete hyperparameters also by adopting a continuous relaxation of the parameters.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Such methods have been extensively used for the optimization of architecture hyperparameters in neural architecture search.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization is a methodology for the global optimization of noisy black-box functions.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In hyperparameter optimization, evolutionary optimization uses evolutionary algorithms to search the space of hyperparameters for a given algorithm.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Repeat steps 2-4 until satisfactory algorithm performance is reached or is no longer improving.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization has been used in hyperparameter optimization for statistical machine learning algorithms, automated machine learning, typical neural network and deep neural network architecture search, as well as training of the weights in deep neural networks.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Population Based Training (PBT) learns both hyperparameter values and network weights.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Multiple learning processes operate independently, using different hyperparameters.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] As with evolutionary methods, poorly performing models are iteratively replaced with models that adopt modified hyperparameter values and weights based on the better performers.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] This replacement model warm starting is the primary differentiator between PBT and other evolutionary methods.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT thus allows the hyperparameters to evolve and eliminates the need for manual hypertuning.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] The process makes no assumptions regarding model architecture, loss functions or training procedures.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT and its variants are adaptive methods: they update hyperparameters during the training of the models.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] On the contrary, non-adaptive methods have the sub-optimal strategy to assign a constant set of hyperparameters for the whole training.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] A class of early stopping-based hyperparameter optimization algorithms is purpose-built for large search spaces of continuous and discrete hyperparameters, particularly when the computational cost to evaluate the performance of a set of hyperparameters is high.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Irace implements the iterated racing algorithm, that focuses the search around the most promising configurations, using statistical tests to discard the ones that perform poorly.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Another early stopping hyperparameter optimization algorithm is successive halving (SHA), which begins as a random search but periodically prunes low-performing models, thereby focusing computational resources on more promising models.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Asynchronous successive halving (ASHA) further improves upon SHA's resource utilization profile by removing the need to synchronously evaluate and prune low-performing models.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperband is a higher level early stopping-based algorithm that invokes SHA or ASHA multiple times with varying levels of pruning aggressiveness, in order to be more widely applicable and with fewer required inputs.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] RBF and spectral approaches have also been developed.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] When hyperparameter optimization is done, the set of hyperparameters are often fitted on a training set and selected based on the generalization performance, or score, of a validation set.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] However, this procedure is at risk of overfitting the hyperparameters to the validation set.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] Therefore, the generalization performance score of the validation set (which can be several sets in the case of a cross-validation procedure) cannot be used to simultaneously estimate the generalization performance of the final model.
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] In order to do so, the generalization performance has to be evaluated on a set independent (which has no intersection) of the set (or sets) used for the optimization of the hyperparameters, otherwise the performance might give a value which is too optimistic (too large).
[src:mlflow/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be done on a second test set, or through an outer cross-validation procedure called nested cross-validation, which allows an unbiased estimation of the generalization performance of the model, taking into account the bias due to the hyperparameter optimization.
[src:mlflow/mlops] The word is a compound of "machine learning" and the continuous delivery practice (CI/CD) of DevOps in the software field.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Machine learning models are tested and developed in isolated experimental systems.
[src:mlflow/mlops] When an algorithm is ready to be launched, MLOps is practiced between data scientists, DevOps, and machine learning engineers to transition the algorithm to production systems.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Similar to DevOps or DataOps approaches, MLOps seeks to increase automation and improve the quality of production models, while also focusing on business and regulatory requirements.
[src:mlflow/mlops] While MLOps started as a set of best practices, it is slowly evolving into an independent approach to ML lifecycle management.
[src:mlflow/mlops] MLOps applies to the entire lifecycle - from integrating with model generation (software development lifecycle, continuous integration/continuous delivery), orchestration, and deployment, to health, diagnostics, governance, and business metrics.
[src:mlflow/mlops] MLOps is a paradigm, including aspects like best practices, sets of concepts, as well as a development culture when it comes to the end-to-end conceptualization, implementation, monitoring, deployment, and scalability of machine learning products.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Most of all, it is an engineering practice that leverages three contributing disciplines: machine learning, software engineering (especially DevOps), and data engineering.
[src:mlflow/mlops] MLOps is aimed at productionizing machine learning systems by bridging the gap between development (Dev) and operations (Ops).
[src:mlflow/mlops] Interest in operationalizing machine learning systems began to grow in the mid-2010s as ML projects started moving from experimentation to production use.
[src:mlflow/mlops] The challenges associated with sustaining such systems were highlighted in a 2015 paper.
[src:mlflow/mlops] The predicted growth in machine learning included an estimated doubling of ML pilots and implementations from 2017 to 2018, and again from 2018 to 2020.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Reports show a majority (up to 88%) of corporate machine learning initiatives are struggling to move beyond test stages.
[src:mlflow/mlops] However, those organizations that actually put machine learning into production saw a 3–15% profit margin increases.
[src:mlflow/mlops] The MLOps market size was USD 2,191.8 Million in 2024, and is projected to be USD 16,613.4 Million in 2030.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Machine Learning systems can be categorized in eight different categories: data collection, data processing, feature engineering, data labeling, model design, model training and optimization, endpoint deployment, and endpoint monitoring.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Each step in the machine learning lifecycle is built in its own system, but requires interconnection.
[src:mlflow/mlops] These are the minimum systems that enterprises need to scale machine learning within their organization.
[src:mlflow/mlops] A standard practice, such as MLOps, takes into account each of the aforementioned areas, which can help enterprises optimize workflows and avoid issues during implementation.
[src:mlflow/mlops] Vendors such as Adaptive ML deliver commercial reinforcement learning operations (RLOps) and MLOps-infrastructure, targeting organizations deploying large language models in production.
[src:mlflow/mlops] A common architecture of an MLOps system would include data science platforms where models are constructed and the analytical engines where computations are performed, with the MLOps tool orchestrating the movement of machine learning models, data and outcomes between the systems.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:mlflow/pipeline-computing] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The first to stress the importance of reproducibility in science was the Anglo-Irish chemist Robert Boyle, in England in the 17th century.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Boyle's air pump was designed to generate and study vacuum, which at the time was a very controversial concept.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Indeed, distinguished philosophers such as René Descartes and Thomas Hobbes denied the very possibility of vacuum existence.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Historians of science Steven Shapin and Simon Schaffer, in their 1985 book *Leviathan and the Air-Pump*, describe the debate between Boyle and Hobbes, ostensibly over the nature of vacuum, as fundamentally an argument about how useful knowledge should be gained.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Boyle, a pioneer of the experimental method, maintained that the foundations of knowledge should be constituted by experimentally produced facts, which can be made believable to a scientific community by their reproducibility.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] By repeating the same experiment over and over again, Boyle argued, the certainty of fact will emerge.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The air pump, which in the 17th century was a complicated and expensive apparatus to build, also led to one of the first documented disputes over the reproducibility of a particular scientific phenomenon.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In the 1660s, the Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens built his own air pump in Amsterdam, the first one outside the direct management of Boyle and his assistant at the time Robert Hooke.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Huygens reported an effect he termed "anomalous suspension", in which water appeared to levitate in a glass jar inside his air pump (in fact suspended over an air bubble), but Boyle and Hooke could not replicate this phenomenon in their own pumps.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] As Shapin and Schaffer describe, "it became clear that unless the phenomenon could be produced in England with one of the two pumps available, then no one in England would accept the claims Huygens had made, or his competence in working the pump".
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Huygens was finally invited to England in 1663, and under his personal guidance Hooke was able to replicate anomalous suspension of water.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Following this Huygens was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] However, Shapin and Schaffer also note that "the accomplishment of replication was dependent on contingent acts of judgment.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] One cannot write down a formula saying when replication was or was not achieved".
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The philosopher of science Karl Popper noted briefly in his famous 1934 book *The Logic of Scientific Discovery* that "non-reproducible single occurrences are of no significance to science".
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Such assertions express a common dogma in modern science that reproducibility is a necessary condition (although not necessarily sufficient) for establishing a scientific fact, and in practice for establishing scientific authority in any field of knowledge.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] However, as noted above by Shapin and Schaffer, this dogma is not well-formulated quantitatively, such as statistical significance for instance, and therefore it is not explicitly established how many times must a fact be replicated to be considered reproducible.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Two major steps are naturally distinguished in connection with reproducibility of experimental or observational studies: when new data are obtained in the attempt to achieve it, the term *replicability* is often used, and the new study is a *replication* or *replicate* of the original one.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Obtaining the same results when analyzing the data set of the original study again with the same procedures, many authors use the term *reproducibility* in a narrow, technical sense coming from its use in computational research.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] *Repeatability* is related to the *repetition* of the experiment within the same study by the same researchers.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Reproducibility in the original, wide sense is only acknowledged if a replication performed by an *independent researcher team* is successful.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The terms reproducibility and replicability sometimes appear even in the scientific literature with reversed meaning, as different research fields settled on their own definitions for the same terms.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In chemistry, the terms reproducibility and repeatability are used with a specific quantitative meaning.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In inter-laboratory experiments, a concentration or other quantity of a chemical substance is measured repeatedly in different laboratories to assess the variability of the measurements.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Then, the standard deviation of the difference between two values obtained within the same laboratory is called repeatability.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The standard deviation for the difference between two measurement from different laboratories is called *reproducibility*.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] These measures are related to the more general concept of variance components in metrology.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The term *reproducible research* refers to the idea that scientific results should be documented in such a way that their deduction is fully transparent.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] This requires a detailed description of the methods used to obtain the data and making the full dataset and the code to calculate the results easily accessible.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] This is the essential part of open science.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] To make any research project computationally reproducible, general practice involves all data and files being clearly separated, labelled, and documented.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] All operations should be fully documented and automated as much as practicable, avoiding manual intervention where feasible.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The workflow should be designed as a sequence of smaller steps that are combined so that the intermediate outputs from one step directly feed as inputs into the next step.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Version control should be used as it lets the history of the project be easily reviewed and allows for the documenting and tracking of changes in a transparent manner.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] A basic workflow for reproducible research involves data acquisition, data processing and data analysis.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Data acquisition primarily consists of obtaining primary data from a primary source such as surveys, field observations, experimental research, or obtaining data from an existing source.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Data processing involves the processing and review of the raw data collected in the first stage, and includes data entry, data manipulation and filtering and may be done using software.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The data should be digitized and prepared for data analysis.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Data may be analysed with the use of software to interpret or visualise statistics or data to produce the desired results of the research such as quantitative results including figures and tables.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The use of software and automation enhances the reproducibility of research methods.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] There are systems that facilitate such documentation, like the R Markdown language or the Jupyter notebook.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The Open Science Framework provides a platform and useful tools to support reproducible research.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Psychology has seen a renewal of internal concerns about irreproducible results (see the entry on replicability crisis for empirical results on success rates of replications).
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Researchers showed in a 2006 study that, of 141 authors of a publication from the American Psychological Association (APA) empirical articles, 103 (73%) did not respond with their data over a six-month period.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In a follow-up study published in 2015, it was found that 246 out of 394 contacted authors of papers in APA journals did not share their data upon request (62%).
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In a 2012 paper, it was suggested that researchers should publish data along with their works, and a dataset was released alongside as a demonstration.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In 2017, an article published in *Scientific Data* suggested that this may not be sufficient and that the whole analysis context should be disclosed.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In economics, concerns have been raised in relation to the credibility and reliability of published research.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In other sciences, reproducibility is regarded as fundamental and is often a prerequisite to research being published, however in economic sciences it is not seen as a priority of the greatest importance.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Most peer-reviewed economic journals do not take any substantive measures to ensure that published results are reproducible, however, the top economics journals have been moving to adopt mandatory data and code archives.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] There is low or no incentives for researchers to share their data, and authors would have to bear the costs of compiling data into reusable forms.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Economic research is often not reproducible as only a portion of journals have adequate disclosure policies for datasets and program code, and even if they do, authors frequently do not comply with them or they are not enforced by the publisher.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] A Study of 599 articles published in 37 peer-reviewed journals revealed that while some journals have achieved significant compliance rates, significant portion have only partially complied, or not complied at all.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] On an article level, the average compliance rate was 47.5%; and on a journal level, the average compliance rate was 38%, ranging from 13% to 99%.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] A 2018 study published in the journal *PLOS ONE* found that 14.4% of a sample of public health statistics researchers had shared their data or code or both.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] There have been initiatives to improve reporting and hence reproducibility in the medical literature for many years, beginning with the CONSORT initiative, which is now part of a wider initiative, the EQUATOR Network.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] This group has recently turned its attention to how better reporting might reduce waste in research, especially biomedical research.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Reproducible research is key to new discoveries in pharmacology.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] A Phase I discovery will be followed by Phase II reproductions as a drug develops towards commercial production.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In recent decades Phase II success has fallen from 28% to 18%.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] A 2011 study found that 65% of medical studies were inconsistent when re-tested, and only 6% were completely reproducible.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Some efforts have been made to increase replicability beyond the social and biomedical sciences.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Studies in the humanities tend to rely more on expertise and hermeneutics which may make replicability more difficult.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Nonetheless, some efforts have been made to call for more transparency and documentation in the humanities.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Hideyo Noguchi became famous for correctly identifying the bacterial agent of syphilis, but also claimed that he could culture this agent in his laboratory.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Nobody else has been able to produce this latter result.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In March 1989, University of Utah chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann reported the production of excess heat that could only be explained by a nuclear process ("cold fusion").
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The report was astounding given the simplicity of the equipment: it was essentially an electrolysis cell containing heavy water and a palladium cathode which rapidly absorbed the deuterium produced during electrolysis.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The news media reported on the experiments widely, and it was a front-page item on many newspapers around the world (see science by press conference).
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Over the next several months others tried to replicate the experiment, but were unsuccessful.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] Nikola Tesla claimed as early as 1899 to have used a high frequency current to light gas-filled lamps from over 25 miles (40 km) away without using wires.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] In 1904 he built Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island to demonstrate means to send and receive power without connecting wires.
[src:mlflow/reproducibility] The facility was never fully operational and was not completed due to economic problems, so no attempt to reproduce his first result was ever carried out.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:mlflow/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:mlflow/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:mlflow/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:mlflow/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:mlflow/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:mlflow/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:mlflow/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:mlflow/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:mlflow/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:mlflow/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:mlflow/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:mlflow/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:mlflow/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:mlflow/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:mlflow/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:mlflow/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:mlflow/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:mlflow/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:mlflow/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:mlflow/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:mlflow/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:mlflow/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:mlflow/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:mlflow/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:mlflow/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:mlflow/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:mlflow/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:mlflow/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:mlflow/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:mlflow/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:mlflow/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:mlflow/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:mlflow/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:mlflow/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:mlflow/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:mlflow/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:mlflow/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:mlflow/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:mlflow/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:mlflow/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:mlflow/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:mlflow/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:mlflow/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:mlflow/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:mlflow/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
